	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Caribbean: WTO reviews Belize's trade policy</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 February 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The review of Belize’s trade policy carried out by the WTO Secretariat notes that ‘agriculture is a major part of Belize’s economy’, representing ‘9% of GDP and 10% of employment in 2008’. The agricultural sector in Belize is characterised by highly diverse production systems and is vulnerable to hurricanes and floods.</p><p>‘Exports are concentrated in only a few products and markets’, with trade patterns being largely preference based (sugar and banana exports to the UK, orange juice and papaya exports to the USA, with these two countries accounting for 71% of Belize’s agricultural exports). Agriculture accounts for half of foreign exchange earnings, despite the recent discovery of oil deposits.</p><p>Restructuring in the banana sector has improved yields in the face of preference erosion on EU markets. The expansion of non-traditional exports (a virtual doubling of orange exports since 1996 and fivefold expansion of papaya exports since 2000) has largely been concentrated in non-EU markets. Belize imports a wide range of food and agricultural products, mainly from the USA (39%), Mexico (15%) and the Netherlands (8%). Belize enjoys a relatively large agricultural trade surplus (with imports at US$107.5 million, and exports at US$147.6 million in 2008).</p><p>The main aim of agricultural policy in Belize is to:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘improve competitiveness …; </li>

<li>‘accelerate diversification; </li>

<li>‘improve and conserve the production base; </li>

<li>‘improve access to resources and services for disadvantaged groups; and </li>

<li>‘strengthen institutional capacities to support the sector.’ </li>

</ul>
<p>Agricultural production is regulated through various legislative acts covering the sugar sector, banana industry, meat and livestock sector, grain markets and citrus production and processing. The government of Belize uses a wide variety of policy tools, including: ‘discretionary import licences; high tariffs; direct purchase of domestic production; research and development programmes; extension services; breeding programmes; disease control measures and product promotion agencies.’</p><p>Import and export licences currently play a central role in government policy and cover (among other products): rice, beans, eggs, flour, fruit and vegetables, meat and meat preparations, sugar and molasses, beer and beverages, maize, milk, poultry meat, jams, jellies, pepper sauce, dry pasta, animal feed and peanuts. State-owned sole import agencies are also appointed for certain imports (onions and rice). Health permits may also be required. Belize does not currently use import quotas. Export licences are required for live animals, sugar, citrus fruits and beans.</p><p>Import duties vary greatly, with an average tariff on agricultural products of 21%. With a few exceptions, import duties are bound at 100%.</p><p>In response to the WTO Secretariat review, the government of Belize highlights the vulnerability of Belize to hurricanes and floods, and the centrality of agriculture to rural poverty reduction. Efforts are directed at structuring production for domestic markets which ‘generate income to producers as well as employment in rural areas’. The government argues that ‘there is strong synchrony between agricultural policy and international trade …. It is increasingly necessary to link both economic growth and poverty eradication to the various dimensions of international trade.’</p><p>The government notes that the diversification that has occurred in response to preference erosion remains largely at ‘the lower end of the global value chains’ (i.e. exports are in primary form). In the CARICOM context, the government of Belize highlights the scope for expanding production to meet regional food security needs.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
WTO, ‘Trade Policy Review: Belize’, access point for Secretariat and government full and summary documents, 3 and 5 November 2010 <br/>

<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp338_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp338_e.htm</a><br/>
<i>Amandla.com.bz</i>, ‘CGA rivals win – portions of citrus act unconstitutional’, 19 March 2010 <br/>
<a href="http://www.amandala.com.bz/index.php?id=9646" target="_self">http://www.amandala.com.bz/index.php?id=9646</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>As in the case of the EU, agricultural policy in Belize is seen as central to the achievement of wider social and economic policy objectives (poverty eradication in rural areas), with policy tools being designed to promote these wider policy objectives.</p><p>The extensive use of import and export licences raises questions about the apparent inconsistency of the current policy of the government of Belize with the provisions of the Caribbean-EU EPA dealing with the abolition of import licences, set out in Article 26.</p><p>It should perhaps be recalled that these provisions reflect a similar commitment under the CARICOM agreement, which has not yet been enforced. The EPA provision thus reinforces an existing commitment to which Belize has signed up in a CARICOM framework, with – significantly – this commitment being extended to imports from the EU. In addition, it should be noted that certain laws regulating agriculture industries have been successfully challenged in the Belize courts and have been deemed to have a negative impact on investments. Similarly, the private sector is calling on the government of Belize to introduce enforceable standards requirements and tariff measures as first steps towards removal of what it considers to be discriminatory price controls and import licensing. It remains to be seen how the government of Belize will now respond to this domestic pressure, as well as the findings of this second WTO Trade Policy Review.</p><p>Turning to the response to preference erosion, it is noteworthy that where diversification of agricultural exports is under way, this is largely serving non-EU markets. This raises the question of the future of the long-term agricultural trade relationship with the EU. In this context, it should be noted that the longer-term aspiration of the Belize agro-food sector is to move towards more value-added products, thereby transforming the basis of the country’s integration into global supply chains, including those serving EU markets.</p>
		</div>
		
